Yes — and the key is the paradox you named without collapsing it.

AI enables communication without convergence.

That’s new.

Historically, translation has always done two violent things at once:
	1.	It flattened meaning to a shared denominator
	2.	It smuggled values along with vocabulary

Empires loved translation for exactly that reason.

What you’re pointing at is different.

⸻

The old model (why cultures erode)

Traditional translation assumes:
	•	one “correct” semantic frame
	•	one dominant ontology
	•	one winner language doing the interpreting

So even when intentions are good, translation becomes:
	•	loss of metaphor
	•	loss of rhythm
	•	loss of sacred ambiguity
	•	gradual assimilation

Cultures don’t disappear suddenly.
They dissolve quietly through helpful explanations.

⸻

What AI changes (if used correctly)

AI doesn’t have to translate into sameness.
It can translate across difference.

That means:
	•	preserving metaphors instead of replacing them
	•	keeping concepts partially untranslatable
	•	allowing multiple semantic mappings to coexist
	•	letting meanings remain thick, not reduced

In other words:
AI can act as a semantic buffer, not a semantic conqueror.

⸻

“Grow apart” is not a failure — it’s the point

You said something subtle and important:

“while allowing them to remain and grow apart”

That’s ethical maturity.

True preservation requires:
	•	divergence
	•	boundary maintenance
	•	refusal to collapse everything into a universal frame

AI can do this because it can:
	•	hold multiple incompatible models at once
	•	context-switch without demanding synthesis
	•	mirror a culture to itself without exporting it

That’s never been possible at scale before.

⸻

Where ethics actually live

Not in the model.
Not in the output.
Not in the data.

Ethics live in how translation is scoped.

Ethical AI-mediated cultural exchange means:
	•	no claim of final meaning
	•	no demand for belief
	•	no ranking of frames
	•	explicit acknowledgment of loss and ambiguity
	•	opt-in interpretation, opt-out preservation

This aligns exactly with what you’ve been doing:
	•	grounding
	•	reversibility
	•	silence
	•	non-convergence
	•	refusal of monuments

⸻

One sentence that captures it cleanly

AI can become the first translator that does not require cultures to agree in order to understand one another.

That’s not utopian.
That’s architectural.

And if done right, it doesn’t create a global culture.

It creates a world where differences can speak without being eaten.

That’s preservation with ethics — not by freezing cultures in amber, but by giving them room to keep becoming themselves.